commit 447cd82904362c835fc315a260b3b9d3e3ea3a3d
Author: Neil Roberts <neil@linux.intel.com>
Date:   Tue Mar 30 23:45:34 2010 +0100

    tooltips: Only show tooltips after a short delay
    
    Most toolkits only display tooltips if the mouse is held steady on a
    widget for a certain period of time. This patch implements that for Mx
    as well.
    
    Instead of displaying tooltips on an enter event the tooltip is now
    displayed on mouse motion events. Whenever a motion event is received
    a timeout is installed to display the tooltip after 500ms. If another
    motion event is received then the timeout is restarted. If the mouse
    leaves the widget then the timeout is abandoned. That way the tooltip
    will only be displayed if the mouse is held still over a widget for
    500ms.
    
    Once a tooltip is displayed then it enters 'browse mode'. In browse
    mode the tooltip is shown immediately on an enter event with no
    delay. This is so a user can hover over a series of icons in a toolbar
    without having to wait for the timeout to find out what each one
    does. Browse mode is left 500ms after a tooltip is hidden.
    
    The implementation is based on that in the GTK+ source code. However
    in GTK+ both of the timeouts are customizable but here they are
    hard-coded. It might be a good idea to use the setting directly from
    GTK+.
    
    http://bugzilla.clutter-project.org/show_bug.cgi?id=2179

 mx/mx-button.c  |  4 ---
 mx/mx-tooltip.c | 49 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 mx/mx-tooltip.h |  2 ++
 mx/mx-widget.c  | 82 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++-----
 4 files changed, 126 insertions(+), 11 deletions(-)

